│ the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in addLocAccess() when calling                   │
│ isa<AllocaInst>(UO) on a null pointer. The underlying object UO is obtained   │
│ via getUnderlyingObjectAggressive(Loc.Ptr), which can return null for certain │
│ poison/undef/phi-cycle patterns. The code assumes UO is always non-null,      │
│ triggering an assertion in isa<> when it's actually null.\n\n2. Analyzing     │
│ opt's Log:\nThe first transformation point is addLocAccess(). The stack trace │
│ shows the assertion failure at isa<AllocaInst>(UO) in FunctionAttrs.cpp:125.  │
│ This indicates that addLocAccess() did not account for a null UO. The         │
│ reproducer uses poison and cyclic phis leading to a situation where           │
│ getUnderlyingObjectAggressive returns null, as hinted by the comment in the   │
│ IR about a null-returning bug.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\naddLocAccess()     │
│ relies on getUnderlyingObjectAggressive() to categorize memory effects into   │
│ local (alloca), argument (Argument or non-identified objects potentially      │
│ being arguments), and other. However, it does not handle the case where       │
│ getUnderlyingObjectAggressive returns null. With UO == nullptr, the           │
│ subsequent isa<AllocaInst>(UO) and isIdentifiedObject(UO) calls are invalid   │
│ and hit assertions. Therefore, the root cause is missing a null check before  │
│ using UO.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nInsert a null check immediately     │
│ after obtaining UO in addLocAccess(). Treat a null underlying object as a     │
│ non-identified object: we cannot prove it is local or a function Argument, so │
│ conservatively mark argmem-only (like the existing non-identified path) and   │
│ 'other' as accessed. Concretely, edit lines 124-136 to:\n\n--- Begin Patch    │
│ ---\nconst Value *UO = getUnderlyingObjectAggressive(Loc.Ptr);\n//            │
│ getUnderlyingObjectAggressive may return null (e.g., due to poison/undef      │
│ or\n// complex cycles). Conservatively treat as non-identified/unknown.\nif   │
│ (!UO) {\n  ME |= MemoryEffects::argMemOnly(MR);\n  ME |=                      │
│ MemoryEffects(IRMemLocation::Other, MR);\n  return;\n}\nif                    │
│ (isa<AllocaInst>(UO))\n  return;\nif (isa<Argument>(UO)) {\n  ME |=           │
│ MemoryEffects::argMemOnly(MR);\n  return;\n}\n\n// If it's not an identified  │
│ object, it might be an argument.\nif (!isIdentifiedObject(UO))\n  ME |=       │
│ MemoryEffects::argMemOnly(MR);\nME |= MemoryEffects(IRMemLocation::Other,     │
│ MR);\n--- End Patch ---\n\nThis preserves the original behavior while adding  │
│ a safe handling path for null UO.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash stems from     │
│ assuming getUnderlyingObjectAggressive never returns null. By adding a null   │
│ check in addLocAccess() and conservatively classifying memory effects when UO │
│ is null, we avoid the assertion and maintain correct, conservative attribute  │
│ inference. This fix prevents the abort in function-attrs on the provided      │
│ reproducer and similar IR patterns."})                                        │
